00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:45.680
I don't think today
he wants to be active.

00:42:45.680 --> 00:42:49.530
The managers don't
call in to Buffett

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:51.475
once a month to give
the numbers and say,

00:42:51.475 --> 00:42:53.600
you know, here's what I'm
doing, what do you think?

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:56.225
And Buffett says, OK, well, you
should get your working capital

00:42:56.225 --> 00:42:58.820
down, or you've got too many
fixed assets, or whatever.

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:01.200
He says, give me great
managers, and then

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:02.820
let them run their business.

00:43:02.820 --> 00:43:04.850
Right?

00:43:04.850 --> 00:43:07.940
And that's sort of his MO now.

00:43:07.940 --> 00:43:12.960
So he's not really claiming
to be a great cast iron

00:43:12.960 --> 00:43:16.370
forger, so he's going to buy
precision cast parts-- you

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:18.300
know, the most recent
deal he did, $40 billion

00:43:18.300 --> 00:43:20.080
or so-- you know.

00:43:20.080 --> 00:43:23.890
It's not that-- he bought
the manager and the company.

00:43:23.890 --> 00:43:26.600
So I think he has
a lot more to say

00:43:26.600 --> 00:43:28.690
about how the capital
gets allocated

00:43:28.690 --> 00:43:30.300
than how the business is run.

00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:32.710
And that's really where
he adds the value.

00:43:32.710 --> 00:43:37.950
AUDIENCE: If you look from
